In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class and work the same way. However, MAUI also introduces more granular lifecycle handling via the `Window` class:

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window equivalent |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |
| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnStopped()` |
| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `OnActivated()` |

**Recommended MAUI approach** â€” override lifecycle methods on your `Window`:

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    protected override void OnCreated()    { base.OnCreated();    /* init */ }
    protected override void OnActivated()  { base.OnActivated();  /* foregrounded */ }
    protected override void OnDeactivated(){ base.OnDeactivated();/* backgrounded */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { base.OnResumed();    /* resumed */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { base.OnStopped();    /* stopped */ }
    protected override void OnDestroying() { base.OnDestroying(); /* cleanup */ }
}
```

Then in your `App` class:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());
```

The `Window`-based approach gives you finer control (e.g., distinguishing "deactivated" from "stopped") and better multi-window support on iPad/desktop.
